241
00:10:45,766 --> 00:10:47,400
As for the Python version,

242
00:10:47,400 --> 00:10:50,533
we'll choose the latest version downloaded from the official website.

243
00:10:50,533 --> 00:10:52,233
After creating the virtual environment,

244
00:10:52,233 --> 00:10:53,933
we must enable it.

245
00:10:53,933 --> 00:10:56,333
So, I press Ctrl + Shift + P again

246
00:10:56,333 --> 00:10:57,766
to bring up the command palette and

247
00:10:57,766 --> 00:11:00,400
select the second option, "Select Interpreter."

248
00:11:00,400 --> 00:11:03,200
Then, apply the `venv` option you just used.

249
00:11:03,200 --> 00:11:04,266
After applying it,

250
00:11:04,266 --> 00:11:06,266
if you open the terminal window and

251
00:11:06,266 --> 00:11:08,566
see `venv` before the command, it

252
00:11:08,566 --> 00:11:11,033
means the virtual environment is enabled.

253
00:11:11,033 --> 00:11:13,533
Now we can safely install necessary tools within this virtual environment. For example,

254
00:11:15,400 --> 00:11:17,566
AI models often use a suite

255
00:11:17,566 --> 00:11:18,900
called PyTorch,

256
00:11:18,900 --> 00:11:20,800
and the pipeline syntax we just practiced

257
00:11:20,800 --> 00:11:23,033
uses the Transformers suite.

258
00:11:23,033 --> 00:11:24,566
Okay, in the window below,

259
00:11:24,566 --> 00:11:25,766
type `pip install` (the

260
00:11:25,766 --> 00:11:27,266
syntax for installing packages)

261
00:11:27,266 --> 00:11:29,700
to enter the names of these two packages

262
00:11:29,700 --> 00:11:32,133
and press Enter to

263
00:11:32,133 --> 00:11:33,400
start the installation. After installation,

264
00:11:33,400 --> 00:11:35,100
we can do a test.

265
00:11:35,100 --> 00:11:37,766
You can open the right-click menu in the blank space of the sidebar

266
00:11:37,766 --> 00:11:40,200
to create a new Python file.

267
00:11:40,200 --> 00:11:42,833
Then paste the syntax we just wrote in Google Colab into it,

268
00:11:44,266 --> 00:11:46,800
press Ctrl + S to save,

269
00:11:46,800 --> 00:11:49,600
and then type `python main.py` at the bottom

270
00:11:49,600 --> 00:11:51,433
to execute the file.

271
00:11:51,433 --> 00:11:53,133
If the settings are correct,

272
00:11:53,133 --> 00:11:54,566
we will

273
00:11:54,566 --> 00:11:57,600
see the same result as Google Colab in the terminal.

274
00:11:57,600 --> 00:11:59,433
Okay, of course, what we can do locally is

275
00:11:59,433 --> 00:12:02,233
not just execute a simple pipeline command.

276
00:12:02,233 --> 00:12:03,466
You can also

277
00:12:03,466 --> 00:12:05,766
make more in-depth adjustments and optimizations according to your needs,

278
00:12:05,766 --> 00:12:07,566
such as integrating multiple different AI models.

279
00:12:07,566 --> 00:12:09,466
To build more complex applications,

280
00:12:09,466 --> 00:12:10,733
and best of all,

281
00:12:10,733 --> 00:12:13,333
even if you're not good at programming, don't worry,

282
00:12:13,333 --> 00:12:16,000
because we can use AI assistants like Claude or Gemini

283
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:18,200
to handle the code.

284
00:12:18,200 --> 00:12:19,833
You just need to write a prompt,

285
00:12:19,833 --> 00:12:22,300
explaining your computer's hardware specifications and requirements.

286
00:12:22,300 --> 00:12:25,433
For example, you might want the AI ​​to recognize the image you provide

287
00:12:25,433 --> 00:12:28,566
and pronounce what it sees.

288
00:12:28,566 --> 00:12:30,900
Okay, so I pasted the prompt and

289
00:12:30,900 --> 00:12:32,933
pressed Enter.

290
00:12:32,933 --> 00:12:34,533
After the AI ​​gave its suggestions,

291
00:12:34,533 --> 00:12:36,433
we can scroll down the page, copy the

292
00:12:36,433 --> 00:12:39,300
necessary package syntax,

293
00:12:39,300 --> 00:12:40,933
paste it into the terminal window,

294
00:12:40,933 --> 00:12:44,233
and press Enter to start the installation.

295
00:12:44,233 --> 00:12:45,733
After the package is installed,

296
00:12:45,733 --> 00:12:48,833
we also copy the code provided by Gemini and paste it

297
00:12:48,833 --> 00:12:51,633
into the original Python file.

298
00:12:51,633 --> 00:12:53,533
Okay, let's do a test.

299
00:12:53,533 --> 00:12:57,700
Gemini mentioned that the image must be named test_image,

300
00:12:57,700 --> 00:13:00,833
so I dragged this image file into the VS Code window

301
00:13:00,833 --> 00:13:03,100
and executed the code.

302
00:13:03,100 --> 00:13:03,833
Similarly, the

303
00:13:03,833 --> 00:13:06,733
first time you execute it, it needs to download the AI ​​model file,

304
00:13:06,733 --> 00:13:08,833
so it takes a long time.

305
00:13:08,833 --> 00:13:11,633
If an error message appears during the process,

306
00:13:11,633 --> 00:13:13,466
you just need to paste the message into Gemini.

307
00:13:13,466 --> 00:13:16,600
Just ask it to help fix and update the code.

308
00:13:16,600 --> 00:13:18,333
If everything goes smoothly,

309
00:13:18,333 --> 00:13:21,600
we'll see the newly generated audio file in the sidebar.

310
00:13:21,600 --> 00:13:24,966
Click "Play" to listen to the AI's recognition results

311
00:13:24,966 --> 00:13:26,200
(in this image).

312
00:13:26,200 --> 00:13:28,366
(We can see a wooden round table)

313
00:13:28,366 --> 00:13:31,433
(on which sits a magazine and a cup of coffee)

314
00:13:31,433 --> 00:13:35,200
(the magazine cover has several interior design photos).

315
00:13:35,200 --> 00:13:37,900
Okay, but sometimes we might encounter a situation

316
00:13:37,900 --> 00:13:40,166
where our computer's hardware isn't powerful enough to

317
00:13:40,166 --> 00:13:42,866
run some larger AI models.

318
00:13:42,866 --> 00:13:46,866
In this case, you can consider using a cloud server for AI computation, which is the

319
00:13:46,866 --> 00:13:50,566
Inference Providers service we introduced earlier.

320
00:13:50,566 --> 00:13:51,466
For example,

321
00:13:51,466 --> 00:13:53,733
suppose I want to use the "cloud" to run the Wan 2.2

322
00:13:53,733 --> 00:13:56,066
video to generate an AI model.

323
00:13:56,066 --> 00:13:59,133
Then we must first obtain a key from Hugging Face

324
00:13:59,133 --> 00:14:01,966
so that the cloud service provider can verify our identity.

325
00:14:01,966 --> 00:14:04,400
So I click "Create New Token,"

326
00:14:04,400 --> 00:14:06,633
give it any name,

327
00:14:06,633 --> 00:14:10,000
and check "Send Request to Inference Providers."

328
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:12,366
Finally, I scroll to the bottom and

329
00:14:12,366 --> 00:14:13,733
click "Create."

330
00:14:13,733 --> 00:14:16,466
Now we can copy the key.

331
00:14:16,466 --> 00:14:17,233
Next,

332
00:14:17,233 --> 00:14:19,166
we can go back to the model page and

333
00:14:19,166 --> 00:14:22,133
click "Use this model" in the upper right corner.  In the

334
00:14:22,133 --> 00:14:23,633
Inference Providers section,

335
00:14:23,633 --> 00:14:25,933
you'll see a piece of code.

336
00:14:25,933 --> 00:14:28,533
You can copy it by pressing Copy.

337
00:14:28,533 --> 00:14:32,000
Since this code uses the Hugging Face Hub suite,

338
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:33,600
in VS Code,

339
00:14:33,600 --> 00:14:36,100
you'll first need to

340
00:14:36,100 --> 00:14:38,833
install it into the virtual environment using `pip install`.

341
00:14:38,833 --> 00:14:40,900
Then, paste the Hugging Face code

342
00:14:40,900 --> 00:14:42,733
into the window above.

343
00:14:42,733 --> 00:14:44,700
As for the API key we just copied,

344
00:14:44,700 --> 00:14:47,733
you can paste it directly into the API Key line.

345
00:14:47,733 --> 00:14:49,766
One important point to note

346
00:14:49,766 --> 00:14:51,500
is that the code provided on the official website

347
00:14:51,500 --> 00:14:55,000
doesn't automatically save the generated video as a video file.

348
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:58,100
Therefore, we must manually create an MP4 file.

349
00:14:58,100 --> 00:15:01,833
Type `wb` to represent "write" and "binary".

350
00:15:01,833 --> 00:15:04,566
The MP4 file is currently empty,

351
00:15:04,566 --> 00:15:06,600
so we need to continue using the `write` syntax to

352
00:15:06,600 --> 00:15:09,366
write the AI-generated video into it.

353
00:15:09,366 --> 00:15:12,666
Finally, close and save the file.

354
00:15:12,666 --> 00:15:14,800
Okay, let's test it using the default prompt,

355
00:15:14,800 --> 00:15:18,433
"A young man is walking on the street".

356
00:15:18,433 --> 00:15:19,266
After a while,

357
00:15:19,266 --> 00:15:21,933
an MP4 file will appear in the sidebar. Click on it to

358
00:15:21,933 --> 00:15:25,066
see the generated video.

359
00:15:25,066 --> 00:15:28,600
Okay, finally, if you're using Hugging Face...  Seeing some useful Spaces and

360
00:15:28,600 --> 00:15:32,366
wanting to run them on your local computer is no problem.

361
00:15:32,366 --> 00:15:35,833
For example, this Space is mainly used to repair blurry old photos.

362
00:15:35,833 --> 00:15:37,600
If you want to download it to your computer,

363
00:15:37,600 --> 00:15:39,566
you can choose "Run Locally."

364
00:15:39,566 --> 00:15:42,266
This will show you a piece of Docker code.

365
00:15:42,266 --> 00:15:44,633
Docker is a well-known software

366
00:15:44,633 --> 00:15:46,533
that can package code and

367
00:15:46,533 --> 00:15:49,266
make it usable anywhere.

368
00:15:49,266 --> 00:15:52,066
So, let's go to the Docker website and

369
00:15:52,066 --> 00:15:55,466
click "Download" to install Docker on our computer.

370
00:15:55,466 --> 00:15:57,533
Then, start it directly.

371
00:15:57,533 --> 00:15:59,500
Following Hugging Face's instructions,

372
00:15:59,500 --> 00:16:01,866
we need to go to Docker's settings page

373
00:16:01,866 --> 00:16:04,366
to enable the Containerized engine feature.

374
00:16:04,366 --> 00:16:05,800
Click "Enable,"

375
00:16:05,800 --> 00:16:07,166
then close Docker and

376
00:16:07,166 --> 00:16:09,566
reopen it to apply the new settings.

377
00:16:09,566 --> 00:16:12,700
Now, we can copy this code.

378
00:16:12,700 --> 00:16:14,866
Open a terminal in the lower right corner of Docker

379
00:16:14,866 --> 00:16:17,266
and paste the code using Ctrl + V. We're

380
00:16:17,266 --> 00:16:19,500
ready to install this Space.

381
00:16:19,500 --> 00:16:20,700
After installation,

382
00:16:20,700 --> 00:16:23,200
a URL will be displayed at the bottom of the terminal.

383
00:16:23,200 --> 00:16:24,966
Clicking it

384
00:16:24,966 --> 00:16:26,533
will open a browser

385
00:16:26,533 --> 00:16:29,500
with the same functionality as the original Space.

386
00:16:29,500 --> 00:16:31,300
Okay, let's do a test.

387
00:16:31,300 --> 00:16:32,833
I dragged a photo from my computer folder...  Take a

388
00:16:32,833 --> 00:16:34,766
slightly blurry old photo,

389
00:16:34,766 --> 00:16:36,900
then click "Submit" at the bottom.

390
00:16:36,900 --> 00:16:39,600
Docker will then launch its local AI model

391
00:16:39,600 --> 00:16:43,300
to generate a high-quality version with significantly improved clarity.

392
00:16:43,300 --> 00:16:47,200
Okay, managing installed Spaces in Docker is also very simple.

393
00:16:47,200 --> 00:16:50,700
You can use the buttons next to them to start or stop them.

394
00:16:50,700 --> 00:16:52,566
And if you no longer need the Space,

395
00:16:52,566 --> 00:16:55,966
just click the trash can button on the far right.

396
00:16:55,966 --> 00:16:58,100
Okay, that's all for today's introduction to Hugging Face. See you next time! Bye!

